WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:14.860
Have you ever, well, have you ever wondered why the people who actually build and maintain and I mean like literally repair the physical world around us, why they seem to capture the absolute least amount of value?

00:15.060 --> 00:18.160
Yeah, the least money, the least power, all of it.

00:18.280 --> 00:27.880
Right. While the people who just kind of, you know, hold the title to an asset or just route the emails about that asset, they capture the most.

00:27.880 --> 00:32.240
It's a really visceral everyday reality for most people.

00:32.420 --> 00:46.060
It really is. Like you look at a hospital, right? The person physically cleaning the hospital rooms makes minimum wage, but the real estate trust that owns the land under the hospital is extracting like billions.

00:46.300 --> 00:50.760
Exactly. And we usually frame this whole thing as a moral failing, you know?

00:50.760 --> 01:00.060
Yeah, we talk about greed or depending on your political leanings, you might talk about the inevitable efficiencies of the free market or whatever.

01:00.660 --> 01:04.080
Just to be clear, we aren't taking a side on that debate today.

01:04.160 --> 01:08.080
Right. No, we're going completely outside those standard frameworks.

01:08.080 --> 01:24.780
Because today's deep dive is looking at a 2026 academic paper by an author named Flyxion, and it is called Ownership Without Understanding, Obstruction, Deskilling, and the Sheaf Theoretic Geometry of Extraction.

01:25.060 --> 01:27.720
Which I know that title alone is a lot.

01:27.740 --> 01:28.760
That's a mouthful, yeah.

01:28.760 --> 01:34.520
But it signals a radical departure from how economists usually talk about this stuff.

01:34.620 --> 01:45.940
I mean, for centuries, classical political economy, so we're talking Adam Smith, David Ricardo, Karl Marx, they've all debated this relationship between capital and labor.

01:46.280 --> 01:52.960
Right. And they usually focus on time or physical effort or, you know, the surplus value extracted from a worker.

01:52.960 --> 02:04.200
Exactly. And even the more modern critiques, like Catherine Liu's work on the professional managerial class, they mostly look at the sociological or cultural ways that different classes hoard power.

02:04.400 --> 02:07.080
But Flyxion just bypasses all of that entirely.

02:07.420 --> 02:17.940
Totally bypasses it. The author introduces this incredibly rigorous, strict mathematical formwork drawn from algebraic topology and geometry.

02:18.580 --> 02:20.700
Which is wild for an economics paper.

02:20.700 --> 02:32.220
It is. But they use it to prove that detaching ownership from the actual hands-on knowledge of how a system works doesn't just create wealth inequality.

02:32.640 --> 02:36.600
It structurally ensures the eventual collapse of that system.

02:37.240 --> 02:42.420
Okay, let's unpack this because it fundamentally rewrites how we diagnose our economy.

02:42.420 --> 02:52.720
You know, usually when we talk about a diagnostic failure in society, we use tools that assume a kind of linear precision, like a medical x-ray, right?

02:52.860 --> 02:55.380
Right. A bone is either broken or it isn't.

02:55.460 --> 03:07.340
Exactly. But when you apply standard economic metrics like GDP growth or quarterly corporate earnings to our current reality, the x-ray looks perfectly healthy.

03:07.340 --> 03:11.280
Oh, yeah. The stock market is up. Productivity software is booming.

03:11.600 --> 03:17.880
But at the exact same time, the bridge is literally collapsing or a software update breaks millions of computers.

03:18.200 --> 03:18.380
Yeah.

03:18.620 --> 03:21.100
And the housing stock is rotting from the inside out.

03:21.260 --> 03:23.800
The traditional diagnostic machine is just broken.

03:24.160 --> 03:25.240
It's totally broken.

03:25.240 --> 03:45.440
So the mission of this deep dive is to take Flyxion's dense mathematics, and it is dense, and translate it into an aha moment that actually explains what you, the listener, see happening at your job, in your neighborhood, and really across the globe.

03:45.440 --> 03:52.280
Yeah. And to do that, the paper first requires us to redefine the basic physics of how work actually happens.

03:52.460 --> 03:53.560
Right. The ground rules.

03:53.560 --> 04:05.620
Exactly. Before we can talk about how a system breaks down or why an owner extracts more than a builder, we have to establish a mathematically sound state description of reality.

04:05.760 --> 04:06.720
Okay. So where do we start?

04:06.980 --> 04:23.080
So Flyxion introduces what they call the RSVP framework. And this applies to literally any production system. It could be a global supply chain, a local housing development, a municipal water grid, or, you know, the code base for a banking app.

04:23.080 --> 04:24.840
Any system where work is happening.

04:25.040 --> 04:33.340
Right. And in the RSVP framework, the state of a system at any given moment is described by three interconnected fields.

04:33.340 --> 04:39.100
So we're kind of mapping an economy the way a physicist would map, like electromagnetic fields in a room.

04:39.460 --> 04:50.640
The analogy is actually quite literal in the math, yeah. So the first field is phi, which is a scalar field representing productive potential or stored capacity.

04:50.640 --> 04:52.640
Okay. Phi is potential.

04:53.020 --> 05:08.240
Think of it as the raw materials just waiting to be transformed. So it's the unmined lithium, the stacked lumber in a storage yard, the unused server compute power, or even just the unallocated budget of a corporation.

05:08.240 --> 05:13.560
It represents the latency of the system, like the pure potential energy of the economy.

05:13.700 --> 05:21.120
Exactly. Now the second field is V, which is a vector field representing directed work and flow.

05:21.120 --> 05:26.840
So if phi is potential energy, V is kinetic energy.

05:26.840 --> 05:44.160
You got it. It encompasses the actual physical and cognitive movement of resources. So when a carpenter physically picks up that lumber and begins to cut it, or when an engineer types lines of code to route data to a server, they are generating the vector field D.

05:44.160 --> 05:46.420
Because it has magnitude and direction.

05:46.620 --> 05:58.480
Right. But the third field is where Flyxion's model really departs from classical economics, because it introduces a thermodynamic reality that standard balance sheets usually just completely ignore.

05:58.640 --> 05:59.920
And this is S, right?

05:59.960 --> 06:00.080
Yeah.

06:00.280 --> 06:00.660
Entropy.

06:00.660 --> 06:21.600
Yes. S stands for entropy. And in standard thermodynamics, entropy is just a measure of disorder in a closed system. But in the context of a production field, entropy represents the hidden costs, the unresolved complexity, material degradation, deferred maintenance.

06:21.960 --> 06:25.340
All the physical incompatibilities that inevitably just pile up.

06:25.380 --> 06:25.580
Yeah.

06:25.580 --> 06:29.280
Because reality naturally drifts toward disorder, right?

06:29.380 --> 06:37.480
Exactly. Wood rots, metal rusts, code bases turn into spaghetti code, pipes degrade, soil depletes.

06:37.800 --> 06:50.260
So this gives us a completely new definition of what labor actually is. Because if phi is the lumber and V is the carpenter moving the lumber, the actual value of the labor isn't just the movement.

06:50.260 --> 06:58.680
No. It's the interaction with the entropy field. Labor in this framework is a local transformation that deliberately lowers entropy.

06:58.900 --> 07:08.500
That is such a crucial insight. So a worker is using specific concrete knowledge of physical constraints to bring order to a chaotic reality.

07:08.500 --> 07:20.400
Right. When a builder constructs a load-bearing wall, they aren't just, you know, expending calories. They are sequencing constraints. They understand the material properties of the wood, local gravity, shear forces.

07:20.600 --> 07:29.120
And they arrange the matter in a highly specific geometry that reduces the structural entropy of that specific region of space.

07:29.120 --> 07:35.700
Exactly. They are forcing the universe to be less messy in a very precise location.

07:36.080 --> 07:50.820
And the way they are compensated for forcing that local order is through a wage. But Flyxion defines the wage mathematically, which I think reveals the root of the whole economic asymmetry we started the show with.

07:50.820 --> 08:00.580
Yeah. The paper defines a wage as a local functional. In math, a functional maps a vector space into its underlying scalar field.

08:01.160 --> 08:08.260
But what that means practically is that the compensation is tied strictly and exclusively to the present state of the system.

08:08.260 --> 08:12.100
To the immediate temporal window where the entropy was actually lowered.

08:12.100 --> 08:19.980
Right. The worker performed in the local transformation, reduces S, and receives a fixed scalar value in return.

08:20.740 --> 08:26.720
The mathematical derivative of that wage with respect to any future state of the asset is just zero.

08:27.180 --> 08:30.320
Let me put that into a concrete scenario for everyone listening.

08:30.500 --> 08:37.740
Think of it like cleaning up a ridiculously messy room or, let's say, a massively overgrown, neglected plot of land.

08:37.820 --> 08:38.880
Okay, yeah, good example.

08:38.880 --> 08:45.320
The worker is out there pulling weeds, testing the soil, digging irrigation trenches.

08:45.980 --> 08:52.860
They are physically battling the entropy field, reducing S by applying their knowledge to the dirt.

08:53.500 --> 08:58.660
And for this, they get paid a local functional, say, $25 an hour.

08:58.840 --> 09:04.020
Right. And that transaction is closed? It is hermetically sealed in the present tense?

09:04.020 --> 09:10.280
Exactly. Now, look at the owner of that land. They might live thousands of miles away.

09:10.740 --> 09:14.960
They've never touched the dirt, never interacted with the V field or the S field.

09:15.640 --> 09:21.000
But their relationship to the asset is defined by completely different math.

09:21.120 --> 09:26.860
Because ownership is modeled as a trajectory claim, instead of a local functional,

09:27.420 --> 09:32.880
the owner's valuation equation integrates over the entire future timeline of the asset.

09:32.880 --> 09:33.800
Which is huge.

09:33.920 --> 09:37.840
Right. The owner captures the delta of the system's value across time,

09:38.060 --> 09:41.040
which includes the entropy lowered by the worker, sure.

09:41.240 --> 09:47.520
But it also includes massive, random outside factors that have absolutely nothing to do with production.

09:47.920 --> 09:51.940
Right. The owner's trajectory claim just absorbs the fact that,

09:52.180 --> 09:56.500
oh, the city decided to build a massive tech hub three miles away,

09:56.500 --> 10:01.420
or global interest rates dropped, or a new subway line got approved.

10:01.420 --> 10:06.200
And suddenly, the land jumps in value by $10 million.

10:06.980 --> 10:13.440
And the worker's local functional, they're $25 an hour, cannot access that future timeline at all.

10:13.760 --> 10:18.080
What's fascinating here is that the structural asymmetry is just laid bare.

10:18.080 --> 10:23.800
However, the worker's compensation explicitly ignores the future timeline of the asset.

10:24.420 --> 10:29.860
And the owner's compensation explicitly ignores the physical reality of the entropy reduction.

10:30.060 --> 10:33.200
They are operating on entirely different mathematical planes.

10:33.480 --> 10:38.500
Yeah. And Flyxion argues that this isn't simply a matter of greedy individuals gaming the system.

10:38.500 --> 10:45.720
The systemic laws of our economy have codified two entirely different functional relationships to reality.

10:46.440 --> 10:49.080
Ownership couples to long-range futures.

10:49.960 --> 10:50.960
Wages do not.

10:51.280 --> 10:53.420
And because of this profound asymmetry,

10:53.980 --> 10:59.020
the paper argues that the economy has fractured into three distinct types of capital or power.

10:59.340 --> 11:04.320
Because the trajectory claim is so much more lucrative than the local functional,

11:04.320 --> 11:10.280
society naturally reorganizes itself to chase the claim rather than the work.

11:10.280 --> 11:13.380
Right. Which leads us to the three-capital taxonomy.

11:14.320 --> 11:18.320
Historically, economic theory always relies on a binary, right?

11:18.880 --> 11:20.100
Capital versus labor.

11:20.720 --> 11:22.180
The owners and the workers.

11:22.440 --> 11:27.780
Yeah, but Flyxion expands this into three capacities of power that govern the production field.

11:28.300 --> 11:32.200
The first is financial capital, denoted as KFA.

11:32.340 --> 11:33.800
And this is pure claim power.

11:33.800 --> 11:37.920
Exactly. It is the capacity to command future resources

11:37.920 --> 11:42.520
simply through holding titles, deeds, patents, and contractual rights.

11:42.960 --> 11:45.920
So this is the hedge fund buying up single family homes.

11:46.340 --> 11:48.860
They aren't building houses. They aren't even managing the plumbers.

11:49.300 --> 11:54.180
They are just accumulating the legal architecture to extract the trajectory claims.

11:54.320 --> 11:58.760
Right. Now, the second capacity is managerial capital or Krum.

11:58.960 --> 12:01.220
Flyxion defines this as routing power.

12:01.220 --> 12:03.500
Routing power. Like directing traffic.

12:03.800 --> 12:10.100
Yeah. This capacity coordinates agents, resources, and workflows through institutional interfaces.

12:10.860 --> 12:16.520
The defining characteristic of managerial capital is that it orchestrates the system

12:16.520 --> 12:20.560
without necessarily knowing how to actually do the work.

12:20.560 --> 12:26.160
Ah. So they manage the APIs, the compliance forms, the project management software.

12:26.420 --> 12:32.340
Exactly. Which maps flawlessly onto Catherine Liu's concept of the professional managerial class.

12:32.780 --> 12:37.720
The PMC are the administrators, the consultants, the directors of operations.

12:38.240 --> 12:41.980
They don't own the trajectory claim like the massive shareholders do,

12:42.200 --> 12:44.840
but they control the flow of the V field.

12:44.840 --> 12:46.920
They tell the workers where to go.

12:47.640 --> 12:49.560
And that brings us to the third capacity.

12:50.800 --> 12:53.660
Embodied ecological capital or key.

12:53.820 --> 12:55.640
And this is constraint knowledge.

12:55.820 --> 13:02.280
Right. It is the actual integrated capacity to build, repair, redesign, or heal a production system

13:02.280 --> 13:06.760
through direct, physical, or deep informational engagement.

13:06.760 --> 13:11.760
So this is the capacity held by the people who actually understand the load-bearing walls

13:11.760 --> 13:16.300
or the intricacies of the server architecture or the biology of a patient.

13:16.740 --> 13:20.320
Exactly. So we have K, the financiers with claim power.

13:20.640 --> 13:23.420
We have KM, the managers with routing power.

13:23.920 --> 13:27.760
And we have K, the practitioners with constraint knowledge.

13:27.760 --> 13:36.240
And Flyxion points out that our modern economy rewards these in the exact opposite order of their actual usefulness, right?

13:36.360 --> 13:43.720
Yeah. The modern hierarchy strictly rewards them as KF is vastly greater than KOM, which is vastly greater than KF.

13:43.840 --> 13:44.020
Yeah.

13:44.160 --> 13:48.560
The financier makes the most, the manager is in the middle, the builder makes the least.

13:48.700 --> 13:53.340
And here is the really devastating mathematical theorem from the paper.

13:53.340 --> 14:03.340
While the market compensates them that way, a complex system can only survive long-term if its internal authority structure is the exact inverse.

14:04.100 --> 14:09.640
Right. Systemic resilience requires K to be greater than KM, which must be greater than KM.

14:09.940 --> 14:14.020
Let me ask everyone listening to picture a massive hospital.

14:14.540 --> 14:16.860
Think about who holds what capital.

14:17.260 --> 14:21.120
The private equity firm that bought the hospital network sits at the top.

14:21.120 --> 14:28.320
They're KFM. They demand a 15% year-over-year return, extracting the trajectory claim.

14:28.560 --> 14:31.940
And right below them are the hospital administrators, the care.

14:32.120 --> 14:41.320
Yeah. They just route the doctors, dictate the 15-minute appointment windows, check compliance boxes to satisfy the private equity firm.

14:41.320 --> 14:50.800
And then at the very bottom of the authority and compensation matrix are the nurses, the biomedical technicians, the attending physicians, the KFs.

14:50.800 --> 14:55.520
Rob's actually stopping human bodies from succumbing to biological entropy.

14:55.720 --> 14:56.140
Exactly.

14:56.640 --> 15:01.640
The administrators have routing power, but they cannot perform a pulmonary bypass.

15:02.280 --> 15:07.720
The private equity firm has claim power, but they cannot operate an MRI machine.

15:07.960 --> 15:08.300
Right.

15:08.300 --> 15:19.060
When the authority of KF and KM supersedes KI, the system begins to optimize for the extraction of the trajectory claim at the expense of entropy reduction.

15:19.620 --> 15:24.760
The administrators cut maintenance budgets, reduce nursing staff, buy cheaper equipment.

15:24.980 --> 15:30.660
And at the local functionals, the wages are suppressed to inflate the trajectory claim.

15:30.660 --> 15:35.780
And the crazy thing is, the spreadsheets at the administrative level look phenomenal.

15:36.320 --> 15:39.660
The KMM interfaces are reporting record efficiency.

15:40.300 --> 15:43.360
But down on the floor, the biological entropy is rising.

15:43.760 --> 15:49.680
Machines break, patients deteriorate, nurses burn out because they have to absorb the excess entropy.

15:50.100 --> 15:53.480
The system looks wealthy, but structurally, it's dying.

15:53.480 --> 16:01.260
I want to directly ask you, the listener, where do you fit in this taxonomy in your day-to-day life?

16:01.620 --> 16:06.600
Are you holding claim power, routing power, or actual constraint knowledge?

16:06.840 --> 16:08.960
It's a really confronting question.

16:09.200 --> 16:22.400
It is, because it forces us to ask, why is managerial capital, KVM, so catastrophically blind to the reality of embodied ecological capital, KVM?

16:22.400 --> 16:28.360
If the managers have all the data dashboards, why can't they see the entropy rising?

16:28.700 --> 16:37.200
Well, to answer that, Flyxion leaves classical economics behind entirely and turns to sheaf theory, which is a branch of algebraic topology.

16:37.420 --> 16:40.060
K-topology. I know this is where the math gets intense.

16:40.240 --> 16:41.700
It does, but it's brilliant.

16:42.140 --> 16:47.640
Sheaf theory is essentially the mathematics of how local data patches together to form global information.

16:48.300 --> 16:52.080
So, to understand a complex system, you start with a production cover.

16:52.080 --> 16:57.960
Right. So, imagine a massive project, like manufacturing an electric vehicle, as a topological space.

16:58.180 --> 17:01.440
You can't build the entire car in a single action.

17:01.640 --> 17:07.680
No, you have to divide the domain into a sequence of overlapping stages, or patches.

17:08.280 --> 17:10.400
So, patch one is the battery chemistry.

17:10.980 --> 17:12.980
Patch two is the chassis fabrication.

17:13.240 --> 17:14.920
Patch three is the wiring harness.

17:15.440 --> 17:17.760
Patch four is software integration.

17:17.760 --> 17:22.720
Got it. And the cover is the collection of all these overlapping patches.

17:23.080 --> 17:23.640
Precisely.

17:24.160 --> 17:31.700
And over this cover lies the competency sheaf, which maps out the distribution of human knowledge across the project.

17:32.100 --> 17:37.620
Flyxion identifies three distinct grades of knowledge within this sheaf, right?

17:37.620 --> 17:39.420
The first is the specialist.

17:39.940 --> 17:43.220
The specialist operates entirely within a single patch.

17:43.640 --> 17:46.880
They know how to fabricate the aluminum chassis flawlessly.

17:47.320 --> 17:50.060
They possess local constraint knowledge.

17:50.400 --> 17:56.720
The second grade is the interface, which sounds exactly like the carom managerial capital we were just talking about.

17:56.880 --> 17:59.500
It is. Interface knowledge operates the boundaries.

17:59.500 --> 18:07.900
A manager knows that the chassis patch must be completed by Thursday and cost under a specific amount, so the wiring patch can start on Friday.

18:08.420 --> 18:09.920
They monitor inputs and outputs.

18:10.100 --> 18:14.420
Right, but they do not possess the internal constraint knowledge of either patch.

18:15.360 --> 18:16.860
And the third grade...

18:16.860 --> 18:19.480
The third grade is where the whole system lives or dies.

18:19.700 --> 18:22.620
Exactly. The third grade is compatibility knowledge.

18:22.620 --> 18:30.680
In sheaf theory, moving from one patch to an overlapping patch requires what is called a restriction map.

18:31.520 --> 18:38.580
You are restricting the data of the larger environment down to the specific physical geometry of the intersection.

18:39.000 --> 18:43.200
So compatibility knowledge is the possession of the gluing data.

18:43.420 --> 18:43.720
Yes.

18:44.280 --> 18:47.880
It is not enough to be a specialist who knows the wiring harness.

18:47.880 --> 18:57.740
You must understand how the physical heat generated by that harness interacts with the thermal limits of the aluminum chassis where the two components overlap.

18:57.960 --> 18:59.420
Here's where it gets really interesting.

19:00.480 --> 19:04.740
Think of managerial knowledge as using an API in software.

19:04.940 --> 19:06.300
Oh, that's a perfect analogy.

19:06.580 --> 19:06.760
Right.

19:07.180 --> 19:11.920
An API is designed to abstract away the internal complexity of a system.

19:11.920 --> 19:17.980
When a manager queries a department, the API just returns a simplified message.

19:18.700 --> 19:21.200
Task complete or task incomplete.

19:21.420 --> 19:22.740
Right. It's a Boolean state.

19:23.160 --> 19:24.860
Let's ground this into physical space.

19:25.840 --> 19:27.620
Think about building a high-rise apartment.

19:28.720 --> 19:33.360
The project manager, who holds KMIM, relies on the institutional API.

19:34.140 --> 19:35.800
They get an email from the plumbing team.

19:36.700 --> 19:38.540
Pipes installed on floor 12.

19:39.340 --> 19:39.680
Success.

19:40.200 --> 19:40.580
Yeah.

19:40.580 --> 19:46.660
The manager roots that success message to the drywall team and schedules them for the next day.

19:47.240 --> 19:49.320
But the manager lacks the gluing data.

19:49.960 --> 19:53.680
They don't know that the plumber installed a pipe half an inch too far from the stud.

19:53.840 --> 19:54.300
Exactly.

19:54.780 --> 19:55.640
The pipe works.

19:56.040 --> 19:57.120
It holds water.

19:57.540 --> 19:59.480
The plumbing patch is locally valid.

19:59.900 --> 20:05.520
But when the drywall patch attempts to intersect with it, the wall physically cannot close.

20:05.640 --> 20:09.540
Because the API failed to capture the spatial incompatibility.

20:09.540 --> 20:12.440
The manager is structurally blind to the overlap.

20:12.440 --> 20:17.420
The interface only tracks the completion of the local section, not the restriction map.

20:17.800 --> 20:27.700
And when the people running the system, the camp owners and the camp managers, only possess interface knowledge, the production field begins to accumulate deep, invisible rot.

20:27.700 --> 20:31.320
Flyxion calls this systemic failure, obstruction, right?

20:31.320 --> 20:31.620
Yes.

20:31.960 --> 20:32.360
Obstruction.

20:32.680 --> 20:39.580
And the paper models this invisible rot using the concept of sec cohomology, specifically sec one-co cycles.

20:40.120 --> 20:40.360
Okay.

20:40.460 --> 20:40.940
Hold on.

20:41.340 --> 20:42.660
Sec one-co cycles.

20:43.160 --> 20:44.860
That sounds intense.

20:44.860 --> 20:45.240
I know.

20:45.300 --> 20:46.100
It sounds like a lot.

20:46.240 --> 20:55.160
But in topology, a one-co cycle basically just measures the failure of local solutions to patch together into a globally consistent state.

20:55.660 --> 20:55.900
Okay.

20:56.020 --> 21:02.500
So when the plumber's pipe and the drywaller's board occupy the exact same physical space, that's a contradiction.

21:02.900 --> 21:03.100
Right.

21:03.260 --> 21:06.800
The local sections are valid, but globally incompatible.

21:07.340 --> 21:11.560
The sec one-co cycle is just the mathematical measurement of that obstruction.

21:11.560 --> 21:18.740
So every time there is a physical or informational contradiction at the boundary of two patches, a co-cycle is born.

21:19.460 --> 21:20.720
The spreadsheet is green.

21:21.240 --> 21:22.640
The API says success.

21:23.300 --> 21:26.220
But the physical reality has an obstruction.

21:26.840 --> 21:38.620
And because the managers cannot see the co-cycles, they make decisions that actively multiply them, which leads to two profound economic pathologies, de-skilling and credential inflation.

21:38.920 --> 21:40.040
Let's start with de-skilling.

21:40.040 --> 21:43.400
Flyxion models this as a sheaf-tearing functor.

21:43.640 --> 21:43.840
Yeah.

21:44.300 --> 21:44.480
Yeah.

21:44.740 --> 21:49.080
In category theory, a functor maps objects from one category to another.

21:49.580 --> 21:54.860
So a sheaf-tearing functor is a process that actively alters the topology of the workplace.

21:54.980 --> 21:55.980
By de-skilling it.

21:56.260 --> 21:56.860
Exactly.

21:57.700 --> 22:07.700
De-skilling is the intentional reorganization of work to make tasks so modular and repetitive that workers no longer need to understand the overlapping patches.

22:07.700 --> 22:11.600
You strip the restriction maps out of the human workforce.

22:11.940 --> 22:17.220
You tear the overlapping intersections so the patches no longer touch in the minds of the workers.

22:17.220 --> 22:23.380
So an employer doesn't want an electrician who also understands drywall and thermal dynamics and framing.

22:24.500 --> 22:25.620
Because that person is expensive.

22:25.880 --> 22:26.720
They have high keys.

22:27.060 --> 22:27.240
Right.

22:27.880 --> 22:34.080
Instead, the employer wants a laborer who only knows how to run a specific wire from point A to point B.

22:34.260 --> 22:35.660
They don't need to know why.

22:35.660 --> 22:38.980
They just execute the local action as fast as possible.

